# Frontend Testing Rules

## Consumer Tests
 - Always type contract definitions using the production request/response types — never define inline types in tests. This binds the contract structurally to the implementation and ensures TypeScript compilation fails if a type changes without updating the contract, which is the only reliable way to prevent stale contracts from reaching `can-i-deploy`
 - Cover the primary success scenario where the API returns 200 with expected response structure
 - Cover error scenarios (4xx, 5xx) only if the consumer implements specific error handling logic based on status codes or error response structures
 - Avoid testing consumer application logic (data transformations, calculations, business rules) in Pact; focus only on HTTP request/response contracts and API client behaviour
 - Prefer like, eachLike, term, and min/max types to avoid over‑specifying volatile data
 - In Pact, the contract is defined by withRequest/willRespondWith; executeTest callback should contain only minimal assertions to verify the request was made (not to validate response data processing)
 
